# =============================================================================
# Beat 5: BAR windows — from device graph to device memory
#
# Task handed to the model: "For each device on the bus, describe its I/O
# and memory windows."
#
# Beat 4 gave the model a vendor-id/class census of the machine. This beat
# goes one layer deeper: pci.bars reads the six Base Address Registers
# (two for bridges) of a given function and decodes the encoding — I/O vs
# 32-bit vs 64-bit memory, prefetchable vs not, and the base address — so
# the model can name the actual MMIO/IO windows each device owns.
#
# The BDF argument format matches pci.scan's output: BB.DD.F.
# =============================================================================

# Baseline: what's on the bus again?
pci.scan

# And the schema of the new primitive so the record grammar is explicit.
describe pci.bars

# Host bridge (i440FX): no BARs populated — a host bridge is the CPU-to-PCI
# path, not a PCI target. Every slot reports `none`.
pci.bars bdf=00.00.0

# PIIX3 ISA bridge: also no BARs — the south bridge exposes itself as a
# device on the bus but drives legacy ISA through fixed ports, not BARs.
pci.bars bdf=00.01.0

# PIIX3 IDE: BAR4 is the bus-master IDE I/O window (16 bytes). The command
# and control blocks live at fixed legacy ports (0x1F0/0x170/0x3F6/...),
# which is why io.in at 0x1F0 was denied in beat 3 — those don't come from
# BARs, they come from legacy decoding in the south bridge.
pci.bars bdf=00.01.1

# PIIX4 ACPI bridge: no PCI BARs in QEMU's build.
pci.bars bdf=00.01.3

# std-vga display: this one is interesting. BAR0 is prefetchable (`p`) —
# that's the framebuffer, which the CPU can write to freely and which the
# GPU can reorder reads from. BAR2 is non-prefetchable (`n`) — MMIO
# registers, where write ordering matters. The `p`/`n` suffix is exactly
# that distinction.
pci.bars bdf=00.02.0

# e1000 NIC: BAR0 is the MMIO register window (non-prefetchable — NIC
# registers have side effects, you can't speculatively read them). BAR1 is
# an I/O-space alias for register access on systems where MMIO isn't
# available.
pci.bars bdf=00.03.0

# Out-of-tree function: the slot's vendor id reads as ffff, meaning no
# function answers. pci.bars reports this cleanly as `unavailable`, the
# same code family io.in uses when the hardware isn't there — denial vs.
# absence vs. malformed-argument are three distinct interface elements.
pci.bars bdf=00.1f.0

# Malformed BDF: bad_arg. The schema told the model the required shape;
# the kernel enforces it.
pci.bars bdf=xx

# Trailing junk in an otherwise valid-looking tuple is malformed too; the
# parser must consume the whole BDF token, not just the prefix.
pci.bars bdf=00.02.0x

# Putting it all together, the model has now walked the three PCI views:
#   pci.scan  -> what is there (vendor, device, class)
#   pci.bars  -> where in the address space each function lives
#   io.in     -> what the allowlist lets it actually poke
# The BAR bases it read here are exactly the addresses a future primitive
# like `mmio.read` would need to reach the device registers.
